    answer: 'Snowflake separates storage (S3/Azure Blob/GCS), compute (Virtual Warehouses), and cloud services (metadata, query planning, auth). Virtual Warehouses are MPP compute clusters that you independently scale and suspend — you pay only when running. The Cloud Services layer handles query parsing, optimization, and metadata — typically billed free up to 10% of compute cost. Multi-cluster warehouses auto-scale horizontally for concurrency by spinning up additional clusters when queue depth exceeds thresholds — no data copying needed since all clusters read the same storage.',
